After a containment failure, Ramesses accepted partial soul-binding to keep the Black Sun Shard dormant.
He became unfinished in service: neither fully alive nor fully dead, tethered to the Pyramid's containment function.
Public murals depict him as the radiant apex of kingship; sealed inscriptions describe his sacrifice and its permanent terms.
He commissioned the Seal College to create the Ushabti — autonomous stone guardians with genuine will to exercise genuine judgment.
The dynasty he founded survived his partial death but could not survive the Ninth Meridian catastrophe's institutional collapse.
His soul-binding is the first documented example of a sovereign accepting cosmic debt to preserve a failing system.
High Priest Amenhotep was his chief administrator, architect of total ritual administration as governance philosophy.
The Solar Court that Ramesses founded is the institutional ancestor of the cleric tradition, the Ushabti, and several Five Cities oversight functions.

